Toggle the Menu and add Escape Key Handling with JavaScript

03
On this page
  1. Enable Menu Toggle Functionality On Page Load
  2. Add an Escape Key Listener to the Submenu Sections
  3. Clearing the Active Menu Item when it’s Clicked

Now that the MegaNav and its submenus are styled, we need to use JavaScript to toggle the active CSS class on and off.

The JavaScript functionality for both of these features has already been written and is included in the project repo.

Feel free to read the code for the final product, or follow along with this lesson to see how the functionality was implemented step by step.

Enable Menu Toggle Functionality On Page Load

Inside of the menu.js file is a function called load.

This function taps into our rendered HTML markup to add interactivity using methods and APIs from the browser DOM, or Document Object Model.

Inside the body of the load function, we select our nav item nodes using document.querySelectorAll to find all of the nodes with the .megamenu-navitem class. The query results in a DOMNodeList that can be converted to an array by wrapping it in Array.from(). This will allow us to call array methods on the collection of elements.

function load() {
  const menuItems = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.megamenu-navitem'))
}
function load() {
  const menuItems = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.megamenu-navitem'))
}

Since we can't reliably grab DOM nodes with JavaScript until the page is fully loaded, at the bottom of the file is an event listener for the DOMContentLoaded the event that will call our load function:

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', load)
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', load)

Inside of the load function, we will iterate through the top-level nav item nodes and do some operations on each to implement toggling of the active class.

For each of the elements, we'll add a click event handler. Inside of the click handler, we'll get a reference to the parent element. Once we have this reference we can check and see if the list of classes contains active. If it doesn't we'll add it, and vice versa to remove.

menuItems.forEach((menuItem, index) => {
	item.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
		let parentElement = menuItem.parentNode
		if (!parentElement.classList.contains('active')) {
			parentElement.classList.add('active')
		} else {
			parentElement.classList.remove('active')
		}
	})
})

menuItems.forEach((menuItem, index) => {
	item.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
		let parentElement = menuItem.parentNode
		if (!parentElement.classList.contains('active')) {
			parentElement.classList.add('active')
		} else {
			parentElement.classList.remove('active')
		}
	})
})

Add an Escape Key Listener to the Submenu Sections

In order to have the menu close when the user hits the Escape key, there are some things we need to add to our function.

First, we'll get our nav submenu items as an array by writing a DOM query selector that looks for the .megamenu-section class.

const submenus = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.megamenu-section'))
const submenus = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.megamenu-section'))

For each of the submenu items, we'll add a keyup event listener that will watch for the Escape key to be pressed.

When this happens, the active class will be removed from the submenu if it is present. Focus will be returned to the parent menu nav button that originally toggled the menu open.

submenus.forEach((submenu) => {
  submenu.addEventListener('keyup', (event) => {
    if (event.key === 'Escape' && submenu.classList.contains('active')) {
      submenu.classList.remove('active')
      submenu.querySelector('.megamenu-navitem').focus()
    }
  })
})
submenus.forEach((submenu) => {
  submenu.addEventListener('keyup', (event) => {
    if (event.key === 'Escape' && submenu.classList.contains('active')) {
      submenu.classList.remove('active')
      submenu.querySelector('.megamenu-navitem').focus()
    }
  })
})

Clearing the Active Menu Item when it’s Clicked

We'll also add a resetSubmenus function inside of our load function, but outside of the menu item loop.

This function will look for an active mega menu section. If the element that is clicked is inside of the active submenu, it will close the menu. This function will be called on every click so the menu can be closed if you click anywhere outside of it.

function resetSubmenus(event) {
  let activeSubmenu = document.querySelector('.megamenu-section.active')
	if (activeSubmenu && !activeSubmenu.contains(event.target)) {
		activeSubmenu.classList.remove('active')
	}
}

document.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
	resetSubmenus(event)
})
